  "prompt": "What are the best websites for architecture students?",
  "response": "Okay, here's a breakdown of the best websites for architecture students, categorized for easier browsing:\n\n**I. Inspiration & Project Showcases:**\n\n*   **ArchDaily:** (archdaily.com) - **The industry standard.** Comprehensive coverage of contemporary architecture, featuring projects, news, interviews, and articles.  They also have ArchDaily China, ArchDaily Brasil, ArchDaily M\u00e9xico, etc. for regional content.  A great place to discover emerging architects and trends.\n*   **Dezeen:** (dezeen.com) - Similar to ArchDaily, but often focuses on a slightly more design-oriented and cutting-edge aesthetic. They also cover interior design, furniture, and product design. Strong news coverage.\n*   **Architizer:** (architizer.com) - Focuses on connecting architects with manufacturers and building product suppliers.  Offers a great project database and annual awards program.\n*   **AIA Architect:** (architectmagazine.com) - Official website of the American Institute of Architects. Provides news, projects, and resources relevant to the profession in the US.\n*   **World-Architects:** (world-architects.com) - Showcases architecture firms from around the world, offering a global perspective.\n*   **e-architect:** (e-architect.com) - Global architecture website with a focus on building designs, news, and travel.\n*   **Divisare:** (divisare.com) - Curated collection of architectural images from around the world. Good for visual inspiration and finding specific details.\n*   **gooood:** (gooood.cn) - A Chinese architecture website, providing a window into the rapidly developing architecture scene in China. (Use a translator if needed).\n*   **Archello:** (archello.com) - Another project database, with a strong focus on products and materials.\n*   **Contemporist:** (contemporist.com) - Focuses on contemporary architecture and design, often showcasing residential projects.\n\n**II. News & Commentary:**\n\n*   **The Architect's Newspaper:** (archpaper.com) -  Focuses on architectural news, urban development, and design in the United States.\n*   **Architectural Record:** (architecturalrecord.com) - A long-standing and respected publication covering architectural projects, news, and technology.\n*   **Metropolis Magazine:** (metropolismag.com) - Examines the cultural, social, and environmental impact of design.\n*   **Domus:** (domusweb.it) -  An Italian architecture and design magazine with an international perspective.  Often features critical essays and theoretical discussions.\n*   **Blueprint:** (blueprintmagazine.co.uk) - A British architecture and design magazine with a focus on contemporary culture.\n\n**III. Tutorials & Resources:**\n\n*   **Show It Better:** (showitbetter.co) - Alex Hogrefe's website is excellent for visualization tips, tutorials, and Photoshop techniques for architectural representation.\n*   **Visualizing Architecture:** (visualizingarchitecture.com) - Jeff Mottle's site offers tutorials and resources for architectural visualization, focusing on software like 3ds Max and V-Ray.\n*   **Ronen Bekerman:** (ronenbekerman.com) - Blog and community for architectural visualization artists.\n*   **Lynda.com/LinkedIn Learning:** (linkedin.com/learning) - Offers a vast library of video tutorials on architecture software, design principles, and professional skills. (Often requires a subscription, but many universities provide access).\n*   **YouTube:** (youtube.com) - Search for specific software tutorials (Revit, AutoCAD, SketchUp, Rhino, etc.), design concepts, or architectural history lectures.  Many architects and educators have their own channels.  Examples: \"The Architectural Student,\" \"30X40 Design Workshop,\" \"Studio N Architects\"\n*   **Skillshare:** (skillshare.com) - Similar to Lynda.com, with a focus on creative skills, including architecture and design.\n*   **Instructables:** (instructables.com) - User-generated tutorials on a wide range of topics, including model making, fabrication, and DIY projects.\n\n**IV. Software & Digital Tools:**\n\n*   **Autodesk:** (autodesk.com) - Home of AutoCAD, Revit, 3ds Max, and other essential software for architects.  They often offer student versions.\n*   **McNeel:** (rhino3d.com) -  The developer of Rhinoceros 3D (Rhino), a powerful NURBS modeling software.\n*   **Graphisoft:** (graphisoft.com) - Makers of ArchiCAD, a BIM (Building Information Modeling) software.\n*   **SketchUp:** (sketchup.com) - User-friendly 3D modeling software, popular for early-stage design and conceptualization.\n*   **Adobe Creative Cloud:** (adobe.com) - Includes Photoshop, Illustrator, InDesign, and other essential tools for architectural representation and communication.\n\n**V.  Academic Resources & Research:**\n\n*   **JSTOR:** (jstor.org) - A digital library of academic journals, books, and primary sources. Useful for research on architectural history, theory, and criticism. (Often requires institutional access).\n*   **Avery Index to Architectural Periodicals:** (columbia.edu) - A comprehensive index of articles on architecture and related topics. (Often requires institutional access).\n*   **Your University Library Website:** Access to online databases, journals, and books relevant to your studies.\n*   **Google Scholar:** (scholar.google.com) - A search engine specifically for scholarly literature.\n\n**VI.  Community & Networking:**\n\n*   **LinkedIn:** (linkedin.com) - Professional networking platform. Connect with architects, designers, and firms. Showcase your work and find job opportunities.\n*   **Behance:** (behance.net) - Adobe's online platform for showcasing creative work.  Great for portfolio building and inspiration.\n*   **Instagram:** (instagram.com) - Use hashtags like #architecture, #architecturedesign, #architectureschool to find inspiration and connect with other students and professionals.\n*   **Pinterest:** (pinterest.com) - Visual discovery engine. Create boards to collect inspiration for design projects, materials, and details.\n*   **Discord & Slack:** Search for architecture-related Discord or Slack communities. These can be great for asking questions, sharing resources, and connecting with peers.\n\n**VII.  Job Boards & Internships:**\n\n*   **Archinect:** (archinect.com/jobs) -  A major architecture job board.\n*   **AIA Career Center:** (aiacareers.org) -  Job board for the American Institute of Architects.\n*   **Indeed:** (indeed.com) - General job board, but you can filter for architecture positions.\n*   **LinkedIn Jobs:** (linkedin.com/jobs) - Use LinkedIn's job search to find architecture internships and jobs.\n*   **Your University's Career Services:** They often have connections with local firms and can help you find internships.\n\n**Tips for Using These Resources:**\n\n*   **Be Specific with Your Searches:** Don't just search for \"architecture.\"  Try \"sustainable architecture,\" \"parametric design,\" \"housing design,\" or specific architects you admire.\n*   **Save and Organize Your Inspiration:** Use Pinterest, Evernote, or another note-taking app to keep track of projects, images, and ideas that inspire you.\n*   **Follow Architects and Firms on Social Media:** Stay up-to-date on their latest projects and news.\n*   **Engage with the Community:** Comment on articles, ask questions in forums, and connect with other students and professionals.\n*   **Don't Just Consume, Create:** Use these resources as inspiration to develop your own design ideas and projects.\n\nThis list should give you a great starting point for exploring the world of architecture online! Good luck with your studies.\n",
